attributes.title: Tokio Marine: Risks Outweighed By Potential Rewards
summary: Tokio Marine's International profits have offset challenges in Japanese operations and North American investments.
Divestments of business-related equities are well underway, boosting growth numbers and profitability.
Despite considerable uncertainties, TKOMF's solid track record and stable dividend warrant recognition.

attributes.content:
In the two years since my first piece on Tokio Marine (TKOMF) (TKOMY), the stock has gone up more than 100%, and for good reason. The Japanese insurer, with its quality earnings and strong growth numbers, does not disappoint. Nor does it evade, readily admitting that certain things - like higher organic profitability - may take longer to achieve. Importantly, the management's plan for realizing sustainable growth is convincing.

In numbers

Starting with FY2022: performance was affected by one-off losses but exceeded internal projections. Focus on cost control and broader operational efficiency (through digital transformation and other measures) solidified around this time.

FY2023 saw an improvement in results: revenue added 12% and net income nearly doubled, led by international profits (which make up more than half of the group total). Global expansion efforts, across Western markets but also Asia, were recharged with a big capital injection.

So far, FY2024 is shaping up well: for the nine months ended 31 December 2024, adjusted net income (excluding capital gains) reached 90% of the full-year projections. On an actual basis, earnings are expected to increase by 70% year-on-year, along a 6% topline growth.

Not everything is rosy, of course. Japanese operation (life and auto segments, in particular) has been recording year-on-year declines due to currency effects as well as increases in claims and provisions. North American investments in commercial loans are too in the red.

Strategy

Divestments of business-related equities, up till end-FY29, form the key strategy to raise profitability metrics. The proceeds are to be used in M&A and for developing additional revenue streams through non-insurance solutions (such as disaster resilience).

Meanwhile, the recently launched Re-New initiative is targeting low-yielding P&C business in Japan. This involves overhauling sales channels and traditional customer-centric practices, to enhance productivity but also in light of regulatory changes.

Embedding technological innovations is also part of the strategy to boost profitability. Data and AI are being employed to reduce administrative burden (by 25% by end-FY26) and support omni-channel operations through digital platforms.

Market

Even on a cursory look, Tokio Marine's multi-pronged approach checks off most of the best-practice recommendations for Japanese insurers. On a macro level, these include overseas expansion, developing non-insurance solutions, deepening domestic insurance business, and optimizing capital allocation.

What's next for Japanese insurers: Ten imperatives for 2025

Naturally, these recommendations have to be read in the context of shifting economic, social, regulatory, and technological environments, both at home and abroad.

The weak yen, for example, was the reason why Tokio Marine's provisions for foreign currency denominated reserves increased, as did derivative costs. The Japanese economy grew by 0.1% in 2024 after a 1.9% expansion the year before; the slowdown is being amplified by the uncertainty around US exports moving forward. Inflation is stubborn, and consumption is sluggish.

In spite of it all, the insurance sector remains surprisingly resilient. The demand for insurance products is buoyed by the country's long-standing demographic trends - aging population coupled with rising life expectancy. Coverage for natural catastrophes and cyber risks are among the growth areas. Japanese insurance is forecast to grow by 3.9% between now and 2029.

Valuation

Tokio Marine (TSE:8766) and the Japanese insurance industry are closely correlated. Only Tokio Marine, among other notable financials, has done better. Its long-term performance is particularly impressive: its three-year total return of 168% exceeded 128% of the industry and 46% of the overall market.

2023 and 2024 have seen remarkable rallies in Japanese stocks driven by a range of different factors (governance reforms, strong results of export firms, etc.). 2025 though has been more modest to date and somewhat volatile, owing to profit-taking and more cautious investor sentiment. Tokio Marine's Tokyo listing is down 6.8% in the last 30 days.

OTC-traded TKOMF is selling at a trailing P/E of 11x against the Financials' median of 12x. This is way below the level at which the stock was valued two years ago (16x) at the time of my initial article. For its growth record and versus global peers (Allianz (ALIZF) 14x, Chubb (CB) 13.6x, Zurich (ZURVY) 16x), Tokio Marine is modestly priced.

Risks

There are substantial risks to the Buy thesis. The Japanese corporate outlook is fragile, and the state of the global economy is compounding the uncertainty, especially for multinationals like Tokio Marine. Some of its investments are already losing value.

The sales of business-related equities reduce investment risk but introduce other complexities. Most significantly, the company's near-term performance may be too reliant on the success of this strategy. In turn, the returns from divestment depend on market conditions, which are hard to predict.

Moreover, since capital gains from divestment are temporary, the management could struggle under the weight of heavy expectations to maintain target profitability and sustainable growth (return on equity of over 20% and organic growth of 7% CAGR according to the Mid-Term Plan).

Conclusion

Despite the risks, what is reassuring is Tokio Marine's track record of execution and discipline. This concerns its past acquisitions, but also wider portfolio management and risk diversification - which I believe will continue to be characteristic of the firm. Dividend, at almost 3%, is notable and has grown impeccably till now. And one can safely assume that dividend return will remain stable, even if annual accretions moderate in the future.

The Japanese stock market may not go up significantly this year, but given imminent catalysts, Tokio Marine is still worth your while.
